Graphical abstract The rational design of new electrocatalysts remains a continuous challenge in pursuing high-performance fuel cells free of precious metals. In this work, we report MN4-type metal-complex catalyst based on bio-inspired systems, i.e., metalloporphyrins complexes that include the second coordination sphere as the central axis for a relevant improvement in catalysis. Two isostructural systems, tetra-ferrocenyl-triazole metalloporphyrin (pocket vs. extended structures), were synthesized to study the role of the second coordination sphere on the electrochemical oxygen reduction reaction (ORR). The electrocatalysis results show that both porphyrin systems promote the ORR via four electrons. The system that presents a pocket structure (o-Fc4TPP-FeIII) exhibits a foot of the wave 72 mV more positive than its analog with an extended structure (p-Fc4TPP-FeIII). Rotating ring-disc experiments evidenced that the presence of H-bonding and distal redox groups would be directly related to faradaic efficiency for the 4-electron reduction to water, with an 86 % for the pocket structure and 76 % for the extended system. This study allows us to confirm the molecular scaffolding function by comparing two systems that present the same functional groups but in different chemical environments, providing valuable information regarding the steric-spatial parameters that play a role in the ORR. Keywords Second coordination sphere Ferrocenyl-metalloporphyrin Oxygen reduction reaction H-bonding and distal redox groups Redox potential Electrocatalysis Data availability No data was used for the research described in the article. 1 Introduction The oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) is considered one of the most important electrochemical reactions in energy conversion devices, such as fuel cells and lithium-air batteries [1]. ORR is a complex and slow process that, in an aqueous medium, depending on pH, can result in obtaining hydrogen peroxide (H2O2/HO2 –, via two electrons) or water (H2O/OH– via four electrons) [2–5] with the 4-electron reduction delivering the most energy in a H2/O2 fuel cell. Although the bond cleavage of the oxygen molecule is thermodynamically favored, its efficiency is low because it requires high overpotentials to promote its unfavorable kinetics [6]. Accordingly, expensive platinum-based catalysts have been the most appropriate materials to catalyze this reaction with high efficiency in fuel cells. The search lower cost materials for alternative systems based on non-precious metals, alloys, and materials derived from carbon and MN4 macrocyclic compounds of transition metals, among others, has been investigated for many years [7,8]. In biological environments, it is possible to find systems that present affinity and reactivity for oxygen, as a process associated with the heme groups in hemoglobin, cytochrome c, chlorophyll, and vitamin B12, among others [7]. These bio-structures have inspired the development of MN4-type macrocycle complexes, i.e., derivatives of metal phthalocyanines and metalporphyrins as redox mediators in catalysis and electrocatalysis [9]. These MN4-based systems have been investigated for more than five decades due to their applications in several areas like electrochemical sensors, photovoltaic devices, molecular electronics, and specially in electrocatalysis, just to name a few [10–13]. Various strategies have been employed to enhance ORR kinetics using MN4-type macrocycle complexes. Among these strategies are periphery functionalization, the addition of a fifth axial ligand (push effect), pyrolysis, and pull effect in meso-substituted macrocycle [14–19]. Some meso-porphyrins have substituents at the ortho position of the phenyl group, which has generated significant interest since it is possible to obtain systems to study the pull effect, also known as the second coordination sphere [20–22]. Thereby, ferrocenyl-triazole meso-tetraphenylporphyrin derivatives of FeIII (FeFc4) were synthesized by Copper-Catalyzed Azide-Alkyne Cycloaddition Reaction (CuAAC), known as “click reaction” to be compared with the FeES4 system, thus evaluating the inclusion of the organometallic fragment [23]. The studies showed that the presence of triazole groups promotes the end-on or axial interaction between oxygen molecule and iron center atom. Related works have determined that the orientation of O2 is essential to determine the reduction mechanism [24], where the side-on configuration promotes reduction via four electrons (4e), while the end-on configuration is through two electrons (2e). However, despite both systems promoting the axial configuration (end-on) due to the presence of substituents in a distal hydrogen bonding environment, they both demonstrated oxygen reduction preferentially via 4e. This result was associated with the additional interaction of the distal hydrogen bonding pocket, which stabilizes the Fe-O2-HN adduct. However, the inclusion of the identical subunits in other positions of the aromatic ring in the meso-position of the macrocycle has not been systematically studied. These researches are crucial to effectively understand the role played by the presence of the pocket structure associated with the second sphere, especially when these compounds work under experimental conditions relevant to ORR. In this work, two structural isomers, α4-meso-tetra-2-(4-ferrocenyl-1,2,3-triazolyl)-phenylporphyrinato iron (III) bromide (o-Fc4TPP-FeIII) and meso-tetra-4-(4-ferrocenyl-1,2,3-triazolyl)-phenylporphyrinato iron (III) bromide (p-Fc4TPP-FeIII) (Fig. 1 ), were synthesized and studied to contribute to understanding the second coordination sphere effect on the performance in the ORR catalysis in basic medium through pocket vs. extended structures. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials and methods All synthetic reactions were performed using standard Schlenk techniques under inert atmosphere. All solvents were purified and dried by conventional methods before use. Reagents ferrocenecarboxaldehyde, 2-nitrobenzaldehyde, 4-nitrobenzaldehyde, trifluoroacetic acid (TFA), pyrrole, sodium nitrite, zinc acetate dihydrate, sodium azide, sodium ascorbate, iron (II) bromide (Aldrich), copper (II) sulfate (Merck) were used as received. Ethynyl ferrocene, and α4-meso-tetra-2-(4-ferrocenyl-1,2,3-triazolyl)-phenylporphyrinato iron (III) bromide (o-Fc4TPP-FeIII) were synthesized following a previously reported procedure [25,26]. NMR spectra were registered on a Bruker AC 400 MHz instrument. 1H NMR chemical shifts were referenced against the chemical shifts of residual solvent resonances. The 1H NMR experiments were obtained with a spectral window of 30 ppm, 32 scans and 4 dummy scans. Infrared spectra were recorded on a Perkin-Elmer Spectrum Two spectrophotometer, with all samples being dispersed in KBr using a solid sample. Mass spectra were acquired on a Thermo Fisher Scientific Velos Pro LTQ linear ion trap mass spectrometer with Z-spray electrospray ionization (ESI). UV–visible spectra were recorded with a Shimadzu spectrophotometer UV-1800. Metalo ligands solutions were prepared using chloroform (CHCl3) as a solvent with a 10−3 mol/L concentration for electrochemical characterization in organic medium. Cyclic voltammetry (CV), linear sweep voltammetry (LSV), and rotating ring-disc electrode (RRDE) studies were carried out at 25 °C using a Metrohm Autolab PGSTAT302N bi-potentiostat with an Analytical Rotator (Metrohm Autolab). All solutions (0.1 M NaOH, 0.1 M Bu4NPF6/CH3Cl) were purged with ultrapure nitrogen or oxygen for 30 min before electrochemical measurements. A modified Edge Plane Graphite (OPG, PineInstruments, USA) was used as a working electrode in CV and LSV, geometrical area of 0.196 cm2. For RRDE experiments, a Glassy Carbon 5 mm area disk Platinum ring (Metrohm Autolab) as a working electrode and a platinum coil having an area of 5 cm2 was used as an auxiliary electrode. A saturated calomel electrode served as the reference electrode. A silver wire with 10 mM silver nitrate and 0.1 M Bu4NPF6 in acetonitrile was used as a reference electrode for non-aqueous solvent. 2.2 Synthesis of the catalyst Isostructural isomers tetra-ferrocenyl-triazole metalloporphyrin (o/p-Fc4TPP-FeIII) were synthesized in several reaction steps (see Supplementary Material). Briefly, the corresponding aminophenyl porphyrin derivatives were converted to azido phenyl porphyrin using sodium nitrite and TFA solution under strict temperature control. Zinc azidoporphyrin derivatives were obtained by metalation reaction of zinc acetate dihydrate in organic solution and the corresponding amino porphyrin. This step is followed by an attachment of the ethynyl ferrocene using a copper-catalyzed azide-alkyne click reaction. Demetallation of the Zinc (II) ferrocenyl porphyrin derivatives are performed by adding concentrated hydrochloric acid in an organic medium, and the free porphyrins are obtained. Finally, o-Fc4TPP-FeIII and p-Fc4TPP-FeIII were obtained by refluxing the free macrocycles in a solution of FeBr2 in THF. The compounds and the precursors were characterized by spectroscopic and electrochemical techniques. 2.3 Preparation of the catalyst-modified OPG electrodes The working electrode was polished with 5-μm sandpaper, rinsed with bi-distilled water (18 MΩ cm) and acetone, and dried under a stream of N2 gas before modification. 10 μL of dilute solutions (1 mg of the compound in 3 mL DMSO) of the catalysts were uniformly distributed on the disc. After 10 min of incubation at room temperature, the surfaces were first immersed in Milli-Q water and then methanol. 2.4 Electrochemical measurements The electrocatalytic study of ORR was carried out by cyclic voltammetry (CV), slow potential scan rate linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) and rotating ring-disk electrode (RRDE). The CV was registered at different potential sweep rates in 0.1 M NaOH saturated O2, and LSV (at 2 mV s−1) both in 0.1 M NaOH in saturated O2. In RRDE experiments the collection efficiency N of the ring electrode was estimated using solutions of Fe(CN)6 3− and gave a value of 25 %, value very close to that reported by the manufacturer (24.9 %). 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Synthesis of catalysts The synthetic methodology used to obtain the meso-tetra-azidophenylporphyrin precursor was carried out based on known methods, using sodium nitrite and sodium azide in an acid medium (TFA). The temperature control in this reaction turned out to be an important issue and the synthesis was performed maintaining a temperature of −10 °C during the reaction. In the initial trials, the reaction was carried out at room temperature and 0 °C. The initial trials were carried out at room temperature and 0 °C. Under these conventional experimental conditions, the product formation was observed, albeit in low yields [27]. However, after purifying and isolating the desired product, the appearance of multiple spots that did not correspond to the precursors or product was observed by silica gel thin layer chromatography (TLC). This behavior is related to the photosensitive and thermal decomposition that a large number of azide derivatives present [28]. To achieve a higher conversion and prevent product decomposition, two parameters were adjusted: the reaction temperature was lowered to −10 °C, and an amber glass vessel was used. Once the azidophenylporphyrin (p-TAzPP-2H) was obtained, this compound was immediately used to obtain the metalated derivative p-TAzPP-Zn. The metalation reaction between p-TAzPP-2H and zinc acetate was carried out under mild reaction conditions (room temperature and without an inert atmosphere), generating the desired product with a quantitative conversion. This reaction step is essential to prevent the incorporation of CuII into the porphyrin ring, a precursor used to generate in situ the catalyst (CuI). This step is necessary for the cycloaddition reaction (CuAAC) between the azido porphyrin and ethynyl ferrocene precursors. The outcome of this process is the generation of the Zn (II) meso-tetra-4-(4-ferrocenyl-1,2,3-triazolyl)-phenylporphyrinate derivative (p-Fc4TPP-Zn) [29]. Subsequently, the demetallation was carried out, where the compound was treated with 32 % HCl to give the free ligand. Finally, free macrocycle reaction in the presence of refluxing FeBr2 produced the p-Fc4TPP-FeIII catalyst in 77 % yield (Scheme 1 ). The complex was filtered on celite® and obtained in pure form without further purification. Purification using a chromatographic column resulted in a color change of the obtained compound, shifting from violet to green. When using silica gel as the stationary phase and a mixture of dichloromethane/methanol (93:7), although it allowed the separation of the precursors from the possible product, the observed color change was likely associated with the generation of the corresponding methoxide (p-Fc4TPP-FeIII-OMe3), which is favored in this type of experimental conditions [30]. The synthetic methodologies and characterizations for the steps depicted are described in detail in the support information section (Fig. S1-6), both for the new catalyst (p-Fc4TPP-FeIII) and the one already reported in the literature (o-Fc4TPP-FeIII) (Figures S7-9). 3.2 Electrochemical behavior The Metalloporphyrins o-Fc4TPP-FeIII (red) and p-Fc4TPP-FeIII (black) were characterized in an organic solution by cyclic voltammetry (Fig. 2 ). In general, the ferrocenyl-triazole meso-TPP-Fe complexes exhibited similar voltammetric behavior in dry chloroform containing 0.1 M Bu4NPF6 as supporting electrolyte. Starting in the anodic direction, both compounds exhibited a clear quasi-reversible process at ∼ 0.25 V attributed to the response of the four ferrocenyl group (FcIII/II process), and then an irreversible wave at ∼ 1.0 V, associated to the oxidation of the porphyrin ring (P/P+) [26]. This assignment was possible by the electrochemical characterization of the TPPFe derivative, which has no ferrocenyl groups or triazole moieties. In this experiment, only the process attributed to the porphyrin ring is observed (Figure S10). The p-Fc4TPP-Fe compound also exhibited a quasi-reversible anodic wave centered at approximately 0.77 V, possibly attributed to the oxidation of the triazole moiety. An experiment using a wider potential window was performed in order to observe if the oxidation of the triazole could be linked to the quasi-reversible ferrocene oxidation (Figure S11a). The results indicated that when a wider potential window is examined, i.e., higher potentials than the ferrocenyl redox process, the ferrocene-associated signal broadens. Furthermore, after multiple scans are performed, incipient passivation of the electrode surface was observed (Figure S11b). This behavior can be associated to the forming radical species and subsequent surface modification. Despite the differences found at potentials higher than 0.5 V vs Ag/Ag+, as expected the redox couples associated with the ferrocenyl fragments showed the same Ep1/2 when comparing both compounds (ortho- and para- positions), which confirms that these functional groups do not present electronic differences related to the position on the aromatic ring of the metalloporphyrins. The inclusion of ferrocenyl fragments in both systems are distal redox centers and play an important role in the selective reduction of O2, as observed in biomimetic functional models of cytochrome c oxidase (Cco) [31]. Regarding the catalytically active site (MN4/FeII), it was not possible to distinguish them by cyclic voltammetry in the region of cathodic potentials in organic medium. Consequently, we proceeded to study their electroactive behavior with the FeN4 molecules confined on a OPG electrode surface under alkaline conditions and investigated their electrocatalytic activity for ORR. 3.3 Electrocatalysis for the ORR on OPG/Porphyrins electrode systems The study for the catalytic activity for the oxygen reduction reaction was carried out using cyclic voltammetry techniques after modifying the OPG working electrode with monolayer levels of the two catalysts under study, o-Fc4TPP-FeIII and p-Fc4TPP-FeIII. The modified electrodes were studied in heterogeneous conditions in aqueous media. Fig. 3 shows the cyclic voltammograms of the systems recorded in a 0.1 M NaOH (pH = 13) deaired electrolyte (N2 purged) and in O2 saturated at 250 mVs−1 (Figure S12 shows a CV at a lower scan rate.). The measurements performed under N2 show the processes associated with the catalytically active iron centers in FeN4 (Fig. 3a), which were not observed in organic media. The structural isomers showed a quasi-reversible process centered at 0.49 V and 0.40 V for the ortho- and para-substituted systems, respectively. In contrast to the redox process of the ferrocenyl group (FcIII/II) in organic media (Fig. 2) the process associated with MN4/FeIII/II is shifted approximately ∼ 0.09 V toward higher potentials than its extended analog. The position of the substituent (Fc-triazole) on the aromatic rings, particularly in the meso-position, modulates the energy levels of the frontier orbitals with d-character of the metal center. As a result, the ortho-substituted system provides an electronic environment that favors the reduction of iron to its more catalytically electroactive (II) oxidation state (Fig. 3b). This is reflected in a more positive FeIII/II redox potential compared to that of the para derivative. Fig. 4 a shows the polarization curves by LSV of modified electrodes. The polarization curves show that the system that structurally contains the pocket site associated with the second coordination sphere (OPG/o-Fc4TPP-FeIII), presents the best performance in terms of onset potential for the ORR in comparison with the extended system (OPG/p-Fc4TPP-FeIII), shifting 72 mV to more positive potentials. The Tafel plots in Fig. 4b obtained from the polarization curves (Fig. 4a), give two linear correlations, with slope values of −47 mV/decade and −66 mV/decade for [OPG/o-Fc4TPP-FeIII] and [OPG/p-Fc4TPP-FeIII] systems, respectively. The Tafel slope of −47 mV for OPG/o-Fc4TPP-FeIII] is close to a hypotethical value of −40 mV/dec that suggests that the rate determining step is a one electron transfer occurring after a fast one-electron transfer step involving the reduction of the FeIII in the complex. The value for p-Fc4TPP-FeIII is within the range reported for iron porphyrins (∼60 mV/dec.), and therefore would suggest that the rate-determining step (rds) is a chemical step preceded by a fast one electron step involving the FeIIIOH + ->FeII + OH– transition. For both complexes the first step is common, but it is intriguing that a slight modification of the ligand seems to change the rate determining step. Both complexes catalyze the reduction of O2 via an overall transfer of 4-electron, which is typical of FeN4 complexes including Fe porphyrins and Fe phthalocyanines [11,17]. It was found that the side-on configuration promotes reduction via four electrons (4e), while the end-on configuration isthroughtwo electrons (2e). The end on interaction does not destabilizes the OO bond enough to promote its rupture. It is also possible that the Fe-O2 binding is strong compared for example to CoN4 macrocyclic. Most CoN4 macrocyclic are known to promote the 2-e reduction of O2 only as Co-O2 binding is weaker compared to that on Fe porphyrins [8]. However, although the pocket system promotes the axial configuration (end-on) due to substituents in a distal hydrogen bonding environment, it preferentially shows an oxygen reduction via 4e. This outcome was associated with the additional interaction of the distal hydrogen bonding pocket, which stabilizes the Fe-O2-HN adduct. The presence of the ferrocenyl moieties play an important role in benefiting the ORR via 4 electron pathways. Metalloporphyrins bearing ferrocene immobilized on self-assembled monolayers (SAMs) of alkanethiols of different chain lengths on Au electrode have been reported to modulate the electron flow [23]. The experiment showed that incorporating the ferrocenyl moieties act as intramolecular electron transfer sites maintain the formation of H2O as the main reaction product via 4 electrons, unlike the FeEs4 macrocyclic, that contained four ester groups (-COOMe) in replaced of organometallic fragments, which generated hydrogen peroxide as the majority reaction product (two electrons) [23]. On the other hand, the interaction of the second coordination sphere associated with the hydrogen bonding interactions facilitates the protonation of distal oxygen, which can be related to the change in the slow reaction stage. Through SERRS-RDE studies, the formation and accumulation of the FeIV = O species have been detected, which is evidence of being the determining stage for this derivative [23,32]. Therefore, it can be established that both pocket (o-Fc4TPP-FeIII) and extend (p-Fc4TPP-FeIII) structures affect the ET mechanism of the reaction, or at least change the Tafel slope. It is interesting to observe the behavior of the LSV down to 0. V. These types of complexes are known for catalyzing the hydrogen evolution reaction; however, as is observed in Fig. 4a with a scan down to 0.0 V no hydrogen evolution was observed (no visible bubble formation) [33]. The limiting currents are not flat but show a slight maximum. The slight decay at more negative potentials could attributed to a decrease of the 4 electrons ORR currents and some peroxide formation. The limiting currents are directly proportional to the total number of electrons transferred. This has also been observed for ORR on graphite modified with Fe phthalocyanines and seems to be a common feature of FeN4 type catalysts in alkaline media [33]. Even though we did not see clear signals in the voltammograms in the absence of O2 that could attributed to the Fe(II)/(I) process (Fig. 3 a), a reduced form of the complex may be formed at more negative potentials that could promote ORR via 2 electrons to form some peroxide [3]. Fig. 5 shows the polarization curves obtained by LSV using a rotating ring-disc electrode, along with the determination of hydrogen peroxide. Although the electrocatalytic studies predominantly indicated that a four-electron mechanism takes place, both systems under study showed the formation of some hydrogen peroxide but much less than bare graphite which only reduces O2 via 2-electrons (see green line Fig. 5). It is also possible that the little peroxide formation observed on both complexes could be attributed to O2 reduction on graphite naked regions on the surface that are not coated by the Fe complexes, but the peroxide response of both complexes is different. In agreement with the polarization curves, although the OPG/p-Fc4TPP-FeIII system presents a higher peroxide percentage than its OPG/o-Fc4TPP-FeIII analog, the ring response of the extended derivative (p-Fc4TPP-FeIII) shows a narrow potential range for peroxide formation (0.52 V vs. RHE). In comparison, the pocket structure generates peroxide at two different potentials (0.58 and 0.13 V vs. RHE). These differences could arise from the contrasting structural characteristics of the extended vs. pocket structure. When these derivatives are deposited on the substrate (OPG), the differences in compound geometry among these derivatives might produce variations in the surface array of coating. This characteristic could leave possible unmodified graphite surface sites, i.e., two different active sites affecting electrocatalytic performance. In the same way, this would explain the peroxide production (ORR via two electrons) observed at 0.13 V vs. RHE for the pocket structure. This is related to the disk-current response at high overpotentials (Fig. 5), where only the OPG/p-Fc4TPP-FeIII system reaches a limit current, meanwhile the o-Fc4TPP-Fe system shows special behavior, i.e., the disk-current decrease at the same potential zone of peroxide formation (0.13 V). The percentage of peroxide production at 0.52 V vs. RHE, was estimated using the following equation: % H 2 O 2 = 2 ∙ I ring / N I disk + I ring / N ∙ 100 For OPG/p-Fc4TPP-FeIII system 24 % peroxide was obtained, while for OPG/o-Fc4TPP-FeIII it reached 14 % peroxide. Our results, especially with the o-Fc4TPP-FeIII catalyst, indicate a significant electrocatalytic performance via 4 electrons compared to the similar systems studied in a homogeneous catalysis, leading to an increase in peroxide generation above 50 % [34,35]. Including distal electroactive fragments would be crucial to favor the selectivity-determining step. The species HO2-FeIII obtained as a product has two possibilities depending on the protonated oxygen (distal vs. proximal). The scheme presented above shows the protonation of the distal oxygen, giving water as a reaction product (OH-basic medium) [36]. However, there is the possibility of protonating the proximal oxygen, which is directly attached to the MN4 metal center, resulting in hydrogen peroxide and only two electrons transferred to regenerate the catalytic cycle. The higher activity catalytic of o-Fc4TPP-Fe compared to p-Fc4TPP-Fe can be explained by the redox mechanism that operates on both complexes (first step of mechanism 1 and 2 involving the fast reduction of FeIIIOH− inactive to FeII active). When polarizing the electrode in the negative direction, catalytic response should start when FeIIIOH is reduced when active sites are electrogenerated on the electrode surface. FeIII(OH) is not active because OH– is strongly bound to the FeIII center and obviously predominates at potentials more positive than the FeIII/II redox potential of each complex. Since o-Fc4TPP-Fe has a more positive FeIII/II redox potential the ORR process should start at a more positive potential, which is experimentally observed, and the opposite is true p-Fc4TPP-Fe. It is interesting to compare the activities of our two complexes with the Fe(IIII)/(II) redox potential which has been proposed as an experimental reactivity descriptor [11–13,18]. Fig. 6 compares the catalytic activity of a great variety of Fe porphyrins and Fe phthalocyanines reported recently [13], with different substituents on the ligand. The kinetic data for our two complexes was taken from the Tafel plots of Fig. 4-b at E = 0.85 V vs RHE. They are illustrated as two sky-blue circles and they follow the general trend of the rest of the macrocyclic, in spite of the dispersion of some Fe porphyrins reported before. The Figure clear shows that the higher activity is exhibited by Fe phthalocyanines with strong electron-withdrawing ligand substituents that weaken the Fe-O2 bond. The low activity of o-Fc4TPP-Fe and to p-Fc4TPP-Fe compared to most Fe phthalocyanines can be associated to a strong Fe-O2 binding energy [11] and also to the fact that at 0.85 V vs RHE most of the surface is coated mostly with inactive Fe(III)OH species as their redox potentials are well below the potential chosen for comparing the activity. This is illustrated in Fig. 6 that in the potential region below 0.85 (vertical green line) Fe(III) predominates on the surface (lower activity) and the opposite is true for complexes on the right side of the green line (higher activity). In other words, the decrease in activity from right to left is associated with a gradual decrease of Fe(II) active sites on the electrode surface at 0.85 V for complexes exhibiting redox potentials below 0.85 V. Those complexes can act as O2 carriers in homogeneous media as hemoglobin as they bind O2 more strongly. 4 Conclusions In this work, isostructural metalloporphyrin derivatives were prepared and characterized. These derivatives were structurally designed to include a catalytically active center (FeN4), H bonds (triazole groups) and distal redox groups (ferrocenyl moieties). Despite both presenting the same functional groups, their electrocatalytic results highlighted the importance of conformation (pocket vs. extend-structure), as evidenced by differences in the Tafel slopes and, consequently, the reaction mechanism. This structural changes also affect their electronic structure which is evidenced by the two different Fe(III)/(II) redox potentials observed for the two complexes. In agreement with previous work, the complex with a more positive redox potential exhibits the higher catalytic activity for ORR. Additionally, the presence of distal redox groups (Fc) in both systems resulted in a high faradaic efficiency. This indicates that their inclusion is crucial for favoring the selectivity-determining step via four electrons pathway, generating water as a primary product, with efficiencies of 93 % for the pocket, and 86 % for the extended-structure, even when measured under heterogeneous conditions. coredata.dc:description: The rational design of new electrocatalysts remains a continuous challenge in pursuing high-performance fuel cells free of precious metals. In this work, we report MN4-type metal-complex catalyst based on bio-inspired systems, i.e., metalloporphyrins complexes that include the second coordination sphere as the central axis for a relevant improvement in catalysis. Two isostructural systems, tetra-ferrocenyl-triazole metalloporphyrin (pocket vs. extended structures), were synthesized to study the role of the second coordination sphere on the electrochemical oxygen reduction reaction (ORR). The electrocatalysis results show that both porphyrin systems promote the ORR via four electrons. The system that presents a pocket structure (o-Fc4TPP-FeIII) exhibits a foot of the wave 72 mV more positive than its analog with an extended structure (p-Fc4TPP-FeIII). Rotating ring-disc experiments evidenced that the presence of H-bonding and distal redox groups would be directly related to faradaic efficiency for the 4-electron reduction to water, with an 86 % for the pocket structure and 76 % for the extended system. This study allows us to confirm the molecular scaffolding function by comparing two systems that present the same functional groups but in different chemical environments, providing valuable information regarding the steric-spatial parameters that play a role in the ORR.
coredata.dc:title: Electrocatalytic oxygen reduction on metalloporphyrins. Second coordination sphere substituents on the ligand: Electronic and steric effects through pocket and extended structures and their effect on the electrocatalytic activity
